					The Future Margaret Thatcher in the Late 1940s
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/thatcher-1940s.jpg
                    
					Margaret Thatcher was born Margaret Hilda Roberts on October 13, 1925, in Lincolnshire. After graduating from Oxford, where she joined the Oxford Union Conservative Association, she worked as a research chemist while cultivating her interest in politics. (SSPL/Getty Images)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Campaigning in Dartford in 1951
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/thatcher-dartford.jpg
                    
					In 1950 Margaret Roberts ran for parliament in the Labour-dominated constituency of Dartford, using the slogan “Vote Right to Keep What’s Left.” The youngest Conservative Party candidate at the time, she lost that year and again in 1951. (Popperfoto/Getty Images)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Thatcher and Her Two Children
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/thatcher-children.jpg
                    
					In December 1951 Margaret married Denis Thatcher, a wealthy businessman. Less than two years later she gave birth to twins, Carol and Mark. Meanwhile, she was studying for the bar exams, which she passed in early 1954. She then spent the next few years practicing law. (Popperfoto/Getty Images)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Thatcher as Secretary of State for Education and Science
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/thatcher-secretary-education.jpg
                    
					Thatcher ran for parliament once more in 1959—this time in the Conservative-dominated constituency of Finchley—and easily won the seat. In 1961 she become parliamentary undersecretary in the Ministry of Pensions and National Insurance. She then steadily moved up the ministerial ranks, becoming secretary of state for education and science when the Conservatives retook power in 1970. (Hulton-Deutsch Collection/Corbis)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Thatcher Holding Her Party’s Manifesto
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/thatcher-party-manifesto.jpg
                    
					In 1975, with the Conservatives back in the opposition, Thatcher defeated former Prime Minister Edward Heath to take over leadership of the party. When the Conservatives won the 1979 election, the “Iron Lady,” as Thatcher became known after denouncing the Soviet Union, became the United Kingdom’s first female prime minister. (Bettmann/Corbis)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Margaret and Denis Thatcher in 1983
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/thatcher-1983.jpg
                    
					Thatcher’s first term was defined by austerity measures, rising unemployment and unrest in Northern Ireland. After seeming to dwindle, her popularity received a boost when she sent British troops to retake the Falkland Islands from Argentina in 1982. The war and an improving economy propelled Thatcher to a second term in 1983. (Bettmann/Corbis)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Thatcher and Reagan in 1987
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/thatcher-reagan.jpg
                    
					Thatcher would remain in office until 1990. Among other things, she would become known for her embrace of free trade and small government, her privatization of state-owned companies, her opposition to the European Union and her close relationship with U.S. President Ronald Reagan. (Peter Jordan//Time Life Pictures/Getty Images)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Thatcher in 2007
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/thatcher-2007.jpg
                    
					Thatcher remained in parliament until 1992, at which time she entered the largely ceremonial House of Lords (as Baroness Thatcher of Kesteven) and began to write her memoirs. She suffered a series of small strokes in the early 2000s and eventually developed dementia. (Pool Photograph/Corbis)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Flowers Outside Thatcher’s Residence
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/margaret-thatcher-tribute.jpg
                    
					One of the 20th century’s most influential politicians, Thatcher died on April 8, 2013, following a stroke. She was 87. (Peter Macdiarmid/Getty Images)
